{"title_page": "Clayton County Library System", "text_new": "{{Infobox library\n| name               = Clayton County Library System\n| logo_size          = \n| logo_alt           = \n| image              = [[File:Clayton_County_Library_System.png|300px]]\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| country            = \n| type               = \n| scope              = \n| established        = 1981\n| dissolved          = \n| ref_legal_mandate  = \n| location           = [[Clayton County, Georgia]]\n| coordinates        = \n| branch_of          = \n| num_branches       = 6\n| items_collected    = \n| collection_size    = 501,321<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|title=About Us - CCLS|url=http://claytonpl.org/about-us/|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n| criteria           = \n| legal_deposit      = \n| req_to_access      = \n| annual_circulation = 456,081 (2015)<ref name=\"GALib2015\" />\n| pop_served         = 269,649 (2015)<ref name=\"GALib2015\">{{cite web|title=Current Look at Georgia Libraries 2015|url=http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-15.pdf|accessdate=3 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224151657/http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-15.pdf|archive-date=24 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| members            = 176,304 (2015)<ref name=\"GALib2015\" />\n| budget             = \n| director           = Rosalind K. Lett\n| num_employees      = \n| website            = http://claytonpl.org\n| references         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Clayton County Library System (CCLS)''' is a [[public library]] system consisting of six branches in the north central portion of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], south of [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]. Its six branches serve 65% of the county population, making it one of the highest attended library systems in Georgia per capita.<ref name=\"GALib2015\" />\n\nCCLS participates in [[Public Information Network for Electronic Services|PINES]], a public library network of 281 libraries in 140 counties throughout Georgia. Any resident of Georgia may receive a PINES library card which allows them access to any of the 8 million books in its collection across the state.<ref name=\"About\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=About PINES|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/about|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> The library is also member of GALILEO, Georgia\u2019s \u2018virtual library\u2019 which facilitates online access to over 100 databases (including magazine articles and online books) for researchers and students on a wide variety of topics.<ref name=\"About\" />\n\n==History==\n===Flint River Regional Library System===\nAn idea for a library in [[Jonesboro, Georgia]] was started in 1941 by the Jonesboro Women's Club. The collection at this time was only 200 books which were housed in the Jones Brothers Department Store on South Main Street.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1960 this small location had grown and joined the Flint River Regional Library System in [[Griffin, Georgia]]. By joining this consortium the members of Jonesboro were able to have access to a much larger selection of books and services. By 1964 the town of Jonesboro was willing to build their own official library to support the library system, and in 1966 opened the Jonesboro Branch.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nOver the next two years the towns of [[Forest Park, Georgia|Forest Park]] and [[Riverdale, Georgia|Riverdale]] opened their own locations, in 1967 and 1968 respectively. By 1975 the Morrow Branch opened in [[Morrow, Georgia]].<ref name=\"History\" />\n\n===Clayton County Library Founding===\nWith four regularly visited branches already established in Clayton, the county opted to form their own independent library system in 1981. By 1988 they constructed the Headquarters Library, the largest library in the system, and the location of the library administration.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1991 the Morrow Branch moved to Maddox Road, and the new construction received critical acclaim in modern architecture by ''Architecture and Urbanism'' magazine.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A+U|journal=Architecture and Urbanism|date=June 1992|issue=261|pages=82\u201389|url=http://msmearch.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/1992_June_A+U_Morrow-Library.pdf|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> In 1998 a new Riverdale Branch was constructed on Valley Hill Road. The Lovejoy Branch was constructed in 2005 along McDonough Road.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nThe most recent addition, a new location for the Forest Park Branch, was completed in 2012.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=CCLS History|url=http://claytonpl.org/history/|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> In 2015 the library received a grant from the [[American Library Association]] and [[Financial Industry Regulatory Authority]] enabling librarians to partner with key organizations in the community to teach financial literacy, home ownership, budgeting, money management, and business ownership.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lett|first1=Rosalind|title=Georgia Library Spotlight - Clayton County Library System|journal=Georgia Library Quarterly|date=April 1, 2017|volume=54|issue=2|url=http://digitalcommons.kennesaw.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2006&context=glq|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Address !! Website \n|-\n| Forest Park Branch || 4812 West Street, Forest Park, GA 30297 || http://claytonpl.org/forest-park/\n|-\n| Headquarters Library || 865 Battle Creek Road, Jonesboro, Georgia 30236 || http://claytonpl.org/headquarters/\n|-\n| Jonesboro Branch || 124 Smith Street, Jonesboro, GA 30236 || http://claytonpl.org/jonesboro/\n|-\n| Lovejoy Branch || 1721 McDonough Road, Hampton, GA 30228 || http://claytonpl.org/lovejoy/\n|-\n| Morrow Branch || 6225 Maddox Road, Morrow, GA 30260 || http://claytonpl.org/morrow/\n|-\n| Riverdale Branch || 420 Valley Hill Road SW, Riverdale, GA 30274 || http://claytonpl.org/riverdale/\n|-\n|}\n\n==Library systems in neighboring counties==\n*[[Atlanta\u2013Fulton Public Library System]] to the north west.\n*[[DeKalb County Public Library]] to the north east.\n*[[Flint River Regional Library System]] to the south west.\n*[[Henry County Library System]] to the south east.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://gapines.org/eg/opac/login?redirect_to=%2Feg%2Fopac%2Fmyopac%2Fmain PINES Catalog]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:County library systems in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox library\n| name               = Clayton County Library System\n| logo_size          = \n| logo_alt           = \n| image              = [[File:Clayton_County_Library_System.png|300px]]\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| country            = \n| type               = \n| scope              = \n| established        = 1981\n| dissolved          = \n| ref_legal_mandate  = \n| location           = [[Clayton County, Georgia]]\n| coordinates        = \n| branch_of          = \n| num_branches       = 6\n| items_collected    = \n| collection_size    = 501,321<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|title=About Us - CCLS|url=http://claytonpl.org/about-us/|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n| criteria           = \n| legal_deposit      = \n| req_to_access      = \n| annual_circulation = 456,081 (2015)<ref name=\"GALib2015\" />\n| pop_served         = 269,649 (2015)<ref name=\"GALib2015\">{{cite web|title=Current Look at Georgia Libraries 2015|url=http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-15.pdf|accessdate=3 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224151657/http://www.georgialibraries.org/lib/publiclibinfo/currentlook/Current_Look_FY-15.pdf|archive-date=24 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| members            = 176,304 (2015)<ref name=\"GALib2015\" />\n| budget             = \n| director           = Rosalind K. Lett\n| num_employees      = \n| website            = http://claytonpl.org\n| references         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Clayton County Library System (CCLS)''' is a [[public library]] system consisting of six branches in the north central portion of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], south of [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]. Its six branches serve 65% of the county population, making it one of the highest attended library systems in Georgia per capita.<ref name=\"GALib2015\" />\n\nCCLS participates in [[Public Information Network for Electronic Services|PINES]], a public library network of 281 libraries in 140 counties throughout Georgia. Any resident of Georgia may receive a PINES library card which allows them access to any of the 8 million books in its collection across the state.<ref name=\"About\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=About PINES|url=http://pines.georgialibraries.org/about|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> The library is also member of GALILEO, Georgia\u2019s \u2018virtual library\u2019 which facilitates online access to over 100 databases (including magazine articles and online books) for researchers and students on a wide variety of topics.<ref name=\"About\" />\n\n==History==\n===Flint River Regional Library System===\nAn idea for a library in [[Jonesboro, Georgia]] was started in 1941 by the Jonesboro Women's Club. The collection at this time was only 200 books which were housed in the Jones Brothers Department Store on South Main Street.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1960 this small location had grown and joined the Flint River Regional Library System in [[Griffin, Georgia]]. By joining this consortium the members of Jonesboro were able to have access to a much larger selection of books and services. By 1964 the town of Jonesboro was willing to build their own official library to support the library system, and in 1966 opened the Jonesboro Branch.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nOver the next two years the towns of [[Forest Park, Georgia|Forest Park]] and [[Riverdale, Georgia|Riverdale]] opened their own locations, in 1967 and 1968 respectively. By 1975 the Morrow Branch opened in [[Morrow, Georgia]].<ref name=\"History\" />\n\n===Clayton County Library Founding===\nWith four regularly visited branches already established in Clayton, the county opted to form their own independent library system in 1981. By 1988 they constructed the Headquarters Library, the largest library in the system, and the location of the library administration.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nIn 1991 the Morrow Branch moved to Maddox Road, and the new construction received critical acclaim in modern architecture by ''Architecture and Urbanism'' magazine.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A+U|journal=Architecture and Urbanism|date=June 1992|issue=261|pages=82\u201389|url=http://msmearch.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/1992_June_A+U_Morrow-Library.pdf|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> In 1998 a new Riverdale Branch was constructed on Valley Hill Road. The Lovejoy Branch was constructed in 2005 along McDonough Road.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\nThe most recent addition, a new location for the Forest Park Branch, was completed in 2012.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=CCLS History|url=http://claytonpl.org/history/|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> In 2015 the library received a grant from the [[American Library Association]] and [[Financial Industry Regulatory Authority]] enabling librarians to partner with key organizations in the community to teach financial literacy, home ownership, budgeting, money management, and business ownership.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lett|first1=Rosalind|title=Georgia Library Spotlight - Clayton County Library System|journal=Georgia Library Quarterly|date=April 1, 2017|volume=54|issue=2|url=http://digitalcommons.kennesaw.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2006&context=glq|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Locations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Address !! Website \n|-\n| Forest Park Branch || 4812 West Street, Forest Park, GA 30297 || http://claytonpl.org/forest-park/\n|-\n| Headquarters Library || 865 Battle Creek Road, Jonesboro, Georgia 30236 || http://claytonpl.org/headquarters/\n|-\n| Jonesboro Branch || 124 Smith Street, Jonesboro, GA 30236 || http://claytonpl.org/jonesboro/\n|-\n| Lovejoy Branch || 1721 McDonough Road, Hampton, GA 30228 || http://claytonpl.org/lovejoy/\n|-\n| Morrow Branch || 6225 Maddox Road, Morrow, GA 30260 || http://claytonpl.org/morrow/\n|-\n| Riverdale Branch || 420 Valley Hill Road SW, Riverdale, GA 30274 || http://claytonpl.org/riverdale/\n|-\n|}\n\n==Library systems in neighboring counties==\n*[[Atlanta\u2013Fulton Public Library System]] to the north west.\n*[[DeKalb County Public Library]] to the north east.\n*[[Flint River Regional Library System]] to the south west.\n*[[Henry County Library System]] to the south east.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://gapines.org/eg/opac/login?redirect_to=%2Feg%2Fopac%2Fmyopac%2Fmain PINES Catalog]\n\n[[Category:County library systems in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clayton_County_Library_System"}
{"title_page": "Claverack Free Library", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Claverack Free Library\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = Claverack Free Library.jpg\n| alt = A small half-shaded white house-like building with green shutters and a white brick chimney\n| caption = Portion of south elevation, 2008\n| locmapin =\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption =\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|13|21|N|73|44|7|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location = [[Claverack-Red Mills, New York|Claverack]], [[New York (state)|NY]]\n| nearest_city = [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]]\n| built = 1932<ref name=\"NRHP nom\">{{cite web|last=Piwonka|first=Ruth|title=National Register of Historic Places nomination, Claverack Free Library|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=1543|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|date=January 1997|accessdate=December 13, 2009}}</ref>\n| architect = Lucius Moore<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n| architecture = [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]]\n| added = 1998\n| designated_nrhp_type = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| refnum = 97001624\n| mpsub = The Architectural and Historic Resources of the Hamlet of Claverack, Columbia County, New York\n| governing_body = Claverack Free Library\n}}\nThe '''Claverack Free Library''' is located on [[New York State Route 23B|NY 23B]] near the center of the [[Administrative divisions of New York#Hamlet|hamlet]] of [[Claverack-Red Mills, New York|Claverack]], New York, United States. It is a small [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] building constructed in the early 1930s from a design by local architect Lucius Moore.\n\nThe library itself formally dates to 1891. It had been in several buildings before the expansion of nearby [[New York State Route 9H|NY 9H]] forced it to move a short distance west to its current building. In 1998 the library building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\n==Building==\n\nThe library is located on the north side of Route 23B, a short distance west of Route 9H. A row of mature trees screen the building from the latter highway. An unpaved driveway on the west leads to parking in the rear. A firehouse is located to the north, and a small former elementary school to the west. A gas station is across the road.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe building itself is a single-story, three-bay [[framing (construction)|frame]] structure on a concrete [[foundation (architecture)|foundation]] sided in beaded wideboard and topped with a [[gable]]d roof shingled in wood pierced by a brick chimney at the west end. A single-story frame wing is on the west elevation.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nTwo small brick steps lead to the main entrance in the center of the south (front) [[facade]]. It is sheltered by a porch with a pair of [[Ionic order|Ionic]] columns supporting an [[entablature]] and [[pediment]]. The paneled main door is flanked by glass sidelights and topped with a [[transom (architectural)|transom]]. The two windows on either side bay have paneled green [[window shutter|shutters]].<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe east facade has a [[Palladian window]] topped by an attic vent. There are three evenly spaced windows on the north (rear) elevation. The west wing, slightly offset from the front, has three windows on the south side and one on the west with similar treatments to the front of the main block.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nInside, the main block has an open, vaulted ceiling. At its west end, lit by the Palladian window, is a fireplace and chimney breast with ornate [[molding (decorative)|moldings]] inspired by 18th century originals. The west wing is partitioned into two spaces. The front one is the children's room; the rear has most of the library's stacks.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\n==History==\n\nThe library began informally in the parlors of the nearby [[Rev. Dr. Elbert S. Porter House|Oakledge]] mansion sometime in the 1880s. Later it moved to an old stone house across what is now Route 9H from the current building. In 1891 it was formally organized as the Claverack Free Library and Reading Room Association.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThat organization soon bought the {{convert|1.5|acre|m2|adj=on}} lot where the current structure is located. An old store that had also served as a post office was converted into the first dedicated library building. It remained adequate for many years, but in the 1920s began to show its age.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nForty years later, in 1931, the state [[New York State Department of Transportation|Highway Department]] was planning to expand Route 9H, an eastern loop from [[U.S. Route 9 in New York|US 9]] between Bell Pond to the south and [[Kinderhook, New York|Kinderhook]] to the north that avoids the city of [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]]. It would be necessary to [[eminent domain|condemn]] the library building, and after several months of negotiations the association accepted an offer of $5,000 (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|5000|1932|r=-3}}}} in contemporary dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}). This would later rise to almost the full $7,800 it would cost to build the present library (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|7800|1932|r=-3}}}} in contemporary dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}). The association turned to alumni of [[Claverack College]], closed 30 years earlier, to make up the difference. It rented space in several houses and other locations for the year it took to build the new library.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe association hired Hudson architect Lucius Moore to adapt a design from models sent to them by the state [[New York State Department of Education|Education Department]]. They selected a small [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] building that had been used, and built for a similar cost, by the library in the [[Long Island]] community of [[Bellport, New York|Bellport]]. The model was slightly adapted to be more consistent with local buildings from the Colonial era. The wideboard siding is beaded, as is the case on 18th-century Claverack houses, and the [[roof pitch]] steeper than the original design.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe first association meeting in the new library was held late in 1932, although the building was not yet quite finished. A thousand-dollar [[bequest]] from one local [[estate (land)|estate]] paid for the furnishings. Moore bought the bronze [[Sconce (light fixture)|sconce]]s on the chimney in New York City at his own expense. The [[woodworking|woodwork]] was custom-milled for the library.\n\nSince its construction, the only significant alteration was the addition of the west wing in 1950. Moore was still practicing, and designed it to be completely sympathetic to the original building. The local [[Lions Club]] donated money for the lighting of the new wing.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n \n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Columbia County, New York]]\n*[[Mid-Hudson Library System]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://claverack.lib.ny.us/ Library website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1932]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival architecture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Claverack, New York]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Columbia County, New York]]\n[[Category:Libraries established in 1891]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Columbia County, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Claverack Free Library\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = Claverack Free Library.jpg\n| alt = A small half-shaded white house-like building with green shutters and a white brick chimney\n| caption = Portion of south elevation, 2008\n| locmapin =\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption =\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|13|21|N|73|44|7|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location = [[Claverack-Red Mills, New York|Claverack]], [[New York (state)|NY]]\n| nearest_city = [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]]\n| built = 1932<ref name=\"NRHP nom\">{{cite web|last=Piwonka|first=Ruth|title=National Register of Historic Places nomination, Claverack Free Library|url=http://www.oprhp.state.ny.us/hpimaging/hp_view.asp?GroupView=1543|publisher=[[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]|date=January 1997|accessdate=December 13, 2009}}</ref>\n| architect = Lucius Moore<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n| architecture = [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]]\n| added = 1998\n| designated_nrhp_type = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| refnum = 97001624\n| mpsub = The Architectural and Historic Resources of the Hamlet of Claverack, Columbia County, New York\n| governing_body = Claverack Free Library\n}}\nThe '''Claverack Free Library''' is located on [[New York State Route 23B|NY 23B]] near the center of the [[Administrative divisions of New York#Hamlet|hamlet]] of [[Claverack-Red Mills, New York|Claverack]], New York, United States. It is a small [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] building constructed in the early 1930s from a design by local architect Lucius Moore.\n\nThe library itself formally dates to 1891. It had been in several buildings before the expansion of nearby [[New York State Route 9H|NY 9H]] forced it to move a short distance west to its current building. In 1998 the library building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\n==Building==\n\nThe library is located on the north side of Route 23B, a short distance west of Route 9H. A row of mature trees screen the building from the latter highway. An unpaved driveway on the west leads to parking in the rear. A firehouse is located to the north, and a small former elementary school to the west. A gas station is across the road.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe building itself is a single-story, three-bay [[framing (construction)|frame]] structure on a concrete [[foundation (architecture)|foundation]] sided in beaded wideboard and topped with a [[gable]]d roof shingled in wood pierced by a brick chimney at the west end. A single-story frame wing is on the west elevation.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nTwo small brick steps lead to the main entrance in the center of the south (front) [[facade]]. It is sheltered by a porch with a pair of [[Ionic order|Ionic]] columns supporting an [[entablature]] and [[pediment]]. The paneled main door is flanked by glass sidelights and topped with a [[transom (architectural)|transom]]. The two windows on either side bay have paneled green [[window shutter|shutters]].<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe east facade has a [[Palladian window]] topped by an attic vent. There are three evenly spaced windows on the north (rear) elevation. The west wing, slightly offset from the front, has three windows on the south side and one on the west with similar treatments to the front of the main block.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nInside, the main block has an open, vaulted ceiling. At its west end, lit by the Palladian window, is a fireplace and chimney breast with ornate [[molding (decorative)|moldings]] inspired by 18th century originals. The west wing is partitioned into two spaces. The front one is the children's room; the rear has most of the library's stacks.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\n==History==\n\nThe library began informally in the parlors of the nearby [[Rev. Dr. Elbert S. Porter House|Oakledge]] mansion sometime in the 1880s. Later it moved to an old stone house across what is now Route 9H from the current building. In 1891 it was formally organized as the Claverack Free Library and Reading Room Association.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThat organization soon bought the {{convert|1.5|acre|m2|adj=on}} lot where the current structure is located. An old store that had also served as a post office was converted into the first dedicated library building. It remained adequate for many years, but in the 1920s began to show its age.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nForty years later, in 1931, the state [[New York State Department of Transportation|Highway Department]] was planning to expand Route 9H, an eastern loop from [[U.S. Route 9 in New York|US 9]] between Bell Pond to the south and [[Kinderhook, New York|Kinderhook]] to the north that avoids the city of [[Hudson, New York|Hudson]]. It would be necessary to [[eminent domain|condemn]] the library building, and after several months of negotiations the association accepted an offer of $5,000 (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|5000|1932|r=-3}}}} in contemporary dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}). This would later rise to almost the full $7,800 it would cost to build the present library (${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|7800|1932|r=-3}}}} in contemporary dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}). The association turned to alumni of [[Claverack College]], closed 30 years earlier, to make up the difference. It rented space in several houses and other locations for the year it took to build the new library.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe association hired Hudson architect Lucius Moore to adapt a design from models sent to them by the state [[New York State Department of Education|Education Department]]. They selected a small [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] building that had been used, and built for a similar cost, by the library in the [[Long Island]] community of [[Bellport, New York|Bellport]]. The model was slightly adapted to be more consistent with local buildings from the Colonial era. The wideboard siding is beaded, as is the case on 18th-century Claverack houses, and the [[roof pitch]] steeper than the original design.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n\nThe first association meeting in the new library was held late in 1932, although the building was not yet quite finished. A thousand-dollar [[bequest]] from one local [[estate (land)|estate]] paid for the furnishings. Moore bought the bronze [[Sconce (light fixture)|sconce]]s on the chimney in New York City at his own expense. The [[woodworking|woodwork]] was custom-milled for the library.\n\nSince its construction, the only significant alteration was the addition of the west wing in 1950. Moore was still practicing, and designed it to be completely sympathetic to the original building. The local [[Lions Club]] donated money for the lighting of the new wing.<ref name=\"NRHP nom\" />\n \n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Columbia County, New York]]\n*[[Mid-Hudson Library System]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://claverack.lib.ny.us/ Library website]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1932]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Libraries on the National Register of Historic Places in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival architecture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Claverack, New York]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Columbia County, New York]]\n[[Category:Libraries established in 1891]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Columbia County, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claverack_Free_Library"}
{"title_page": "Clark County Public Library", "text_new": "'''Clark County Public Library''' is the [[public library]] of [[Clark County, Ohio|Clark County]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]. It is based in [[Springfield, Ohio|Springfield]], [[Ohio]] and has a collection of approximately 500,000 items.\n\n==History==\nThe Clark County Public Library traces its beginnings to the [[Springfield Lyceum]] in 1841 in [[Springfield, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/history.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122010346/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/history.shtml |archivedate=2010-01-22 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref> Various short-lived library associations followed and the library found a more permanent home on the second floor of Black's Opera House. The library housed 3,300 volumes when it opened to the public at this location in 1872. As patronage and the collection expanded, the need for yet another move set in and the library relocated in 1877 to the second floor of the Union Hall Building, which was situated on what is today Fountain Avenue.\n\n[[File:Warder Public Library.jpg|thumb|right|Warder Literacy Center, formerly the Warder Public Library]]\nLocal entrepreneur Benjamin Warder gave the library a new location on the corner of High Street in 1890, with a building constructed in memory of his parents and dedicated to the people of Springfield. This location now houses the Warder Literacy Center. Library service continued to expand and grow at this new location. The year 1936 saw the library's first [[bookmobile]] service to the area, with a homemade [[Trailer (vehicle)|trailer]] that could carry 500 books. The 1950s and 1960s brought about the expansion of the library in the form of branches at Park Shopping Center, Southern Village Shopping Center, and in the villages of [[Enon, Ohio|Enon]] and [[South Charleston, Ohio|South Charleston]].\n\nThe main library moved from the [[Warder Public Library]] to its new facility on Fountain Avenue in 1989.  The library has five locations throughout Clark County. It also has one bookmobile that covers 41 community stops, 7 schools, 14 daycare centers and 5 Head Start Programs.\n\nThe library's collection includes over 425,000 books, 425 magazine subscriptions, 4,000 CDs, over 3,000 DVDs and Blu-ray (including an Express DVD collection), Video Games for check-out (Xbox One, Xbox 360, PS3, PS4, Wii and Wii U), eBooks and magazines, many online resources such as Gale Courses, full (in library) access to Ancestry.com and framed art for check-out (Main Library).\n\nThe library offers many cultural and educational programs throughout the year at all of its branches. The Speaker Series (2000-2010) brought national and regional authors, artists, and lecturers to Springfield. Past participants included [[Sean Astin]], [[Stan Lee]], [[Maya Angelou]], [[Dave Barry]], [[Mary Higgins Clark]], [[Doris Kearns Goodwin]], and [[Elie Wiesel]]. The library's annual Summer Reading Program is popular with area children along with our weekly storytimes.  Also on offer are different programs like LEGO Club, Teen TAC and Animanga Club, the Springfield Writes Local Author Fair, One-On-One Tech Classes and much more.  A full listing of upcoming activities can be found on the library's web calendar at https://web.archive.org/web/20150925202523/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/calendar.  You can also connect with the library on Facebook at  https://www.facebook.com/ClarkCountyPublicLibrary, Twitter at https://twitter.com/ClarkLibraryOH, and on Wordpress at https://clarkcopubliclibrary.wordpress.com/.\n\n==Branches==\n*Main Library, [[Springfield, Ohio]]<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/main_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002171610/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/main_library.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Park Branch, also in Springfield, Ohio<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/park_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002172111/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/park_library.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Southern Village Branch, also in Springfield, Ohio<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/southern_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910010159/http://ccpl.lib.oh.us/southern_library.shtml |date=2006-09-10 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Houston Branch, [[South Charleston, Ohio]]<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/houston_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002171504/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/houston_library.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Indian Mound Branch, [[Enon, Ohio]]<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/indian_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910141742/http://ccpl.lib.oh.us/indian_library.shtml |date=2006-09-10 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Bookmobile<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/bookmobile.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002171546/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/bookmobile.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Clark County, Ohio]]\n*[[Public library]]\n*[[Springfield, Ohio]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttp://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/content/library\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20151016050913/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/hrsloc\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us Clark County Public Library Website]\n\n{{coord|39.922065|-83.810642|display=title|region:US-OH_type:landmark}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Springfield, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Education in Clark County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "'''Clark County Public Library''' is the [[public library]] of [[Clark County, Ohio|Clark County]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]. It is based in [[Springfield, Ohio|Springfield]], [[Ohio]] and has a collection of approximately 500,000 items.\n\n==History==\nThe Clark County Public Library traces its beginnings to the [[Springfield Lyceum]] in 1841 in [[Springfield, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/history.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122010346/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/history.shtml |archivedate=2010-01-22 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref> Various short-lived library associations followed and the library found a more permanent home on the second floor of Black's Opera House. The library housed 3,300 volumes when it opened to the public at this location in 1872. As patronage and the collection expanded, the need for yet another move set in and the library relocated in 1877 to the second floor of the Union Hall Building, which was situated on what is today Fountain Avenue.\n\n[[File:Warder Public Library.jpg|thumb|right|Warder Literacy Center, formerly the Warder Public Library]]\nLocal entrepreneur Benjamin Warder gave the library a new location on the corner of High Street in 1890, with a building constructed in memory of his parents and dedicated to the people of Springfield. This location now houses the Warder Literacy Center. Library service continued to expand and grow at this new location. The year 1936 saw the library's first [[bookmobile]] service to the area, with a homemade [[Trailer (vehicle)|trailer]] that could carry 500 books. The 1950s and 1960s brought about the expansion of the library in the form of branches at Park Shopping Center, Southern Village Shopping Center, and in the villages of [[Enon, Ohio|Enon]] and [[South Charleston, Ohio|South Charleston]].\n\nThe main library moved from the [[Warder Public Library]] to its new facility on Fountain Avenue in 1989.  The library has five locations throughout Clark County. It also has one bookmobile that covers 41 community stops, 7 schools, 14 daycare centers and 5 Head Start Programs.\n\nThe library's collection includes over 425,000 books, 425 magazine subscriptions, 4,000 CDs, over 3,000 DVDs and Blu-ray (including an Express DVD collection), Video Games for check-out (Xbox One, Xbox 360, PS3, PS4, Wii and Wii U), eBooks and magazines, many online resources such as Gale Courses, full (in library) access to Ancestry.com and framed art for check-out (Main Library).\n\nThe library offers many cultural and educational programs throughout the year at all of its branches. The Speaker Series (2000-2010) brought national and regional authors, artists, and lecturers to Springfield. Past participants included [[Sean Astin]], [[Stan Lee]], [[Maya Angelou]], [[Dave Barry]], [[Mary Higgins Clark]], [[Doris Kearns Goodwin]], and [[Elie Wiesel]]. The library's annual Summer Reading Program is popular with area children along with our weekly storytimes.  Also on offer are different programs like LEGO Club, Teen TAC and Animanga Club, the Springfield Writes Local Author Fair, One-On-One Tech Classes and much more.  A full listing of upcoming activities can be found on the library's web calendar at https://web.archive.org/web/20150925202523/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/calendar.  You can also connect with the library on Facebook at  https://www.facebook.com/ClarkCountyPublicLibrary, Twitter at https://twitter.com/ClarkLibraryOH, and on Wordpress at https://clarkcopubliclibrary.wordpress.com/.\n\n==Branches==\n*Main Library, [[Springfield, Ohio]]<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/main_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002171610/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/main_library.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Park Branch, also in Springfield, Ohio<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/park_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002172111/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/park_library.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Southern Village Branch, also in Springfield, Ohio<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/southern_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910010159/http://ccpl.lib.oh.us/southern_library.shtml |date=2006-09-10 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Houston Branch, [[South Charleston, Ohio]]<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/houston_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002171504/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/houston_library.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Indian Mound Branch, [[Enon, Ohio]]<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/indian_library.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910141742/http://ccpl.lib.oh.us/indian_library.shtml |date=2006-09-10 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n*Bookmobile<ref>http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/bookmobile.shtml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002171546/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/bookmobile.shtml |date=2006-10-02 }}. URL accessed 21 September 2006.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Clark County, Ohio]]\n*[[Public library]]\n*[[Springfield, Ohio]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\nhttp://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/content/library\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20151016050913/http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us/hrsloc\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ccpl.lib.oh.us Clark County Public Library Website]\n\n{{coord|39.922065|-83.810642|display=title|region:US-OH_type:landmark}}\n\n[[Category:Public libraries in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Springfield, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Education in Clark County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clark_County_Public_Library"}
